WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.400
Hi, I'm Max Kuhn. I'm a statistician and work as a software engineer at RStudio. I mostly

00:00:12.400 --> 00:00:17.799
focus on open source tools for building models. I run the tidymodels group, and tidymodels

00:00:17.799 --> 00:00:21.879
is a collection of R packages that have very similar syntax and design principles to the

00:00:21.879 --> 00:00:26.480
Tidyverse. So we've made a lot of improvements to tidymodels in the last six months. Some

00:00:26.480 --> 00:00:31.120
of those improvements have been around user interfaces. So we have better ways of specifying

00:00:31.120 --> 00:00:36.000
which predictors are added to a model. We've made other improvements around computational

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:41.040
efficiency. So we have limited support now for sparse matrices and expanded support for

00:00:41.040 --> 00:00:45.639
payload processing. Now what I'd like to talk about more in this video is a specific package

00:00:45.639 --> 00:00:50.639
that we just released called FineTune. And FineTune is an expansion of our Tune package

00:00:50.639 --> 00:00:55.520
and gives two additional ways to optimize hyperparameters or tuning parameters in models.

00:00:55.560 --> 00:00:59.480
Now those are types of parameters that can't be directly estimated from the data, such

00:00:59.480 --> 00:01:03.360
as the number of neighbors in a k-nearest neighbor model. And so one variation we'll

00:01:03.360 --> 00:01:09.040
look at in this presentation is a new method of doing grid search. And the other method

00:01:09.040 --> 00:01:14.760
is another iterative method called simulated annealing.

00:01:14.760 --> 00:01:17.800
To illustrate the methods that we'll talk about today, we'll use a cell segmentation

00:01:17.800 --> 00:01:23.919
data from the model data package. It's a two-class classification problem with about 58 numeric

00:01:24.080 --> 00:01:29.199
predictors. We use a support vector machine. And for the support vector machine, there's a variety

00:01:29.199 --> 00:01:34.320
of tuning parameters, such as the cost value or the radial basis function kernel parameter called

00:01:34.320 --> 00:01:38.879
sigma. And then this talk will be about two different ways of finding optimal parameters

00:01:38.879 --> 00:01:45.120
of these values. Now these tuning parameter values are important. They have a big influence

00:01:45.120 --> 00:01:50.720
on the model fit and performance. The problem is we can't directly estimate them from the data.

00:01:51.040 --> 00:01:55.760
So we need to find good ways of coming up with values for those two parameters, even

00:01:55.760 --> 00:01:59.879
though we can't directly estimate them. To measure performance, we'll use tenfold cross

00:01:59.879 --> 00:02:05.080
validation, and we'll measure the errand of the R-C curve. Now the model definitions and

00:02:05.080 --> 00:02:08.639
the complete code set that you can use to reproduce these analyses are shown at the

00:02:08.639 --> 00:02:13.679
link here.

00:02:13.679 --> 00:02:17.279
So to give some visual demonstration of what we're trying to do, what I did is I took these

00:02:17.279 --> 00:02:21.960
two different tuning parameters and generated a very large grid and re-sampled them. And

00:02:21.960 --> 00:02:26.639
that gives a sense of what the truly best result would be from our search. And you can

00:02:26.639 --> 00:02:31.119
see here on the left-hand side this contour plot. Blue values indicate poor performance

00:02:31.119 --> 00:02:36.360
of the R-C curve, and then white values are more optimal. And so you can see the lower

00:02:36.360 --> 00:02:41.399
diagonal of the search space is pretty flat and not very good. And as you go to the upper

00:02:41.399 --> 00:02:46.080
diagonal, there's sort of like a little mountainous ridge that has good performance values. And

00:02:46.080 --> 00:02:50.960
the best performance value on the left-hand side plot is shown by the black dot. And any

00:02:50.960 --> 00:02:56.559
really point along the ridge that goes from that black dot sort of down towards the southeast

00:02:56.559 --> 00:03:01.119
will give us pretty good performance. The problem is if we go over that ridge, that

00:03:01.119 --> 00:03:04.479
dark spot there, which you can see a little bit better on the right-hand side surface

00:03:04.479 --> 00:03:10.039
plot, gives really, really poor performance. So we want to find the values of these tuning

00:03:10.039 --> 00:03:14.880
parameters, and we'll be trying to find the best ones, which are indicated in the white

00:03:14.880 --> 00:03:23.639
on the plots. Now, the first method we'll talk about is something called racing methods.

00:03:23.639 --> 00:03:27.600
And this is sort of an alteration of grid search that's been around for quite a while.

00:03:27.600 --> 00:03:32.440
Now in ordinary grid search, what you would do is come up with a candidate set of parameter

00:03:32.440 --> 00:03:37.440
values that you want to try. And then you'd measure their performance, usually using resampling,

00:03:37.440 --> 00:03:42.039
and then pick the one that seems to be best or has the characteristics that you like. Now,

00:03:42.039 --> 00:03:46.360
the problem with this is you have to evaluate a potentially large number of models to get

00:03:46.360 --> 00:03:51.119
performance estimates until you can make a decision. So let's say we do 20 values of

00:03:51.119 --> 00:03:56.000
the support vector machine tuning parameters, and we use tenfold cross-validation. That

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:00.320
would be about 200 total model fits, and we can't make a decision on which tuning parameters

00:04:00.320 --> 00:04:04.559
are good or bad until we do all that work. So what racing methods do is they sort of

00:04:04.559 --> 00:04:09.619
incrementally evaluate the resamples. So in the first couple resamples, you proceed as

00:04:09.619 --> 00:04:14.860
normal and measure their performance. And then what you do subsequently is do an interim

00:04:14.860 --> 00:04:19.660
analysis after each resample to figure out, basically, are there tuning parameters that

00:04:19.660 --> 00:04:23.859
have a low probability of being called the best results? And so one way we could do that

00:04:23.859 --> 00:04:28.260
is we could fit an ANOVA model to those results, where the outcome is, let's say, the errand

00:04:28.260 --> 00:04:33.619
of the RC curve, or whatever performance metric you want to use. And the predictive factor

00:04:33.619 --> 00:04:39.859
is the qualitative tuning parameter combinations, like, you know, model 1, model 12, and so

00:04:39.859 --> 00:04:44.899
on. And so what we can do is we can evaluate those and see which ones are statistically

00:04:44.899 --> 00:04:50.420
different from the best possible. And if they are, we can discard them. Now, there's another,

00:04:50.420 --> 00:04:54.899
there's a variety of ways to do racing methods. We have a second one implemented in FineTune

00:04:54.899 --> 00:04:58.980
that uses win-loss statistics and something called the Bradley-Terry model, and treats

00:04:58.980 --> 00:05:02.959
these data as if they were a sports competition. And if you want to learn more about these

00:05:02.959 --> 00:05:08.399
methods and particularly how we implemented them here, there's a paper there from 2014

00:05:08.399 --> 00:05:13.399
that has the details. And for our particular example, we'll use a grid of 20 support vector

00:05:13.399 --> 00:05:18.559
machine candidate values that are generated with a space-filling design. And we'll show

00:05:18.559 --> 00:05:24.880
how racing can be used to efficiently evaluate them compared to ordinary grid search.

00:05:24.880 --> 00:05:29.559
So let's illustrate the race. So let's say we take our 10 folds and we randomly arrange

00:05:29.559 --> 00:05:34.279
them so they're in a random order. We would take the first fold and do what we'd normally

00:05:34.279 --> 00:05:40.079
do. We'd compute our models and then make predictions and measure, let's say, the area

00:05:40.079 --> 00:05:47.160
of the RC curve. Now, in the plot, what you see is on the y-axis is just the model number,

00:05:47.160 --> 00:05:50.839
which is just sort of arbitrarily numbered. There's 20 of them. And on the x-axis, we

00:05:50.839 --> 00:05:57.640
see the measure of performance. And so the blue dot for model 12 indicates that it had

00:05:57.640 --> 00:06:01.679
the best performance across all the tuning parameter values. And then the rest of the

00:06:01.679 --> 00:06:06.640
points show the loss of performance compared to the current best. So you can see model

00:06:06.640 --> 00:06:11.200
12 was the current best, but model 17 was close behind. And on the bottom there, model

00:06:11.200 --> 00:06:15.559
16 did not have very good performance. And so this is after we've evaluated the first

00:06:15.559 --> 00:06:18.839
resample. Now, in the second resample, we do the same

00:06:18.839 --> 00:06:25.559
thing. We just resample and compute the performance metrics for all 20 tuning parameter values.

00:06:25.559 --> 00:06:30.720
Now, in this plot, instead of the individual RC values, these points represent the average

00:06:30.720 --> 00:06:37.399
of two ROC area under the curve values for each model. Now, the leaders switch from model

00:06:37.399 --> 00:06:42.079
12 to model 17. But you can still see that there's a variety of different models that

00:06:42.079 --> 00:06:45.519
do not have very good performance compared to those.

00:06:45.519 --> 00:06:51.679
Now, in iteration 3, we start doing the interim analysis. In this case, we're going to be

00:06:51.679 --> 00:06:55.839
talking about the ANOVA method. And what that allows us to do is put a confidence interval

00:06:55.839 --> 00:07:00.559
on the loss of performance compared to the leader for each tuning parameter value. And

00:07:00.559 --> 00:07:04.920
so you can see the ones that are in black, there's no evidence to reject that they're

00:07:04.920 --> 00:07:08.799
statistically different from the best value in blue. But the ones in gray that you can

00:07:08.799 --> 00:07:12.679
see are statistically different from that. And therefore, we think it would be a pretty

00:07:12.679 --> 00:07:17.399
good idea to discard them from further consideration. So basically, we use the ANOVA statistics

00:07:17.399 --> 00:07:22.000
to figure out which tuning parameter values to keep resampling and which ones we can get

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:26.359
rid of. And in this particular case, in the third iteration, we're getting rid of 17 different

00:07:26.359 --> 00:07:28.480
tuning parameter values.

00:07:28.480 --> 00:07:34.600
Now, on iteration 4, the confidence interval is tightened up pretty considerably. And model

00:07:34.600 --> 00:07:38.959
1 there falls out to where we're left with two models. And as we keep resampling, you

00:07:38.959 --> 00:07:44.200
can see that we're getting closer and closer to having one fall out. And then iteration

00:07:44.200 --> 00:07:50.839
9 of 10, model 12 finally is discarded because it's not statistically or because it is statistically

00:07:50.839 --> 00:07:52.679
different than the best.

00:07:52.679 --> 00:07:58.679
So this is on the ninth fold out of 10. What we normally do is if we have any situation

00:07:58.679 --> 00:08:03.359
where there's only one left over, we keep resampling it till it has the full precision

00:08:03.359 --> 00:08:09.140
that we would like to measure performance. So after nine iterations, basically, we filter

00:08:09.140 --> 00:08:14.380
out all but one tuning value combination. And then we just resample model 17 once. And

00:08:14.380 --> 00:08:19.140
what the result is, instead of fitting the full set of 200 model fits, we actually considered

00:08:19.140 --> 00:08:24.260
74 model fits. So it's a pretty substantial reduction in both time and evaluations of

00:08:24.260 --> 00:08:25.380
models.

00:08:25.380 --> 00:08:30.779
And since our interval analysis method is not very slow, we're able to call these values

00:08:30.779 --> 00:08:35.179
pretty quickly. And so the nice thing about racing is you can do a very large grid if

00:08:35.179 --> 00:08:40.260
you'd like and do it pretty efficiently because chances are you will not be resampling the

00:08:40.260 --> 00:08:44.820
full grid for all of the possible resamples.

00:08:44.820 --> 00:08:49.419
The code for racing is shown here. It's very similar to the tune grid function in the tune

00:08:49.419 --> 00:08:53.219
package. And you can see that we first set the seed so we make sure we get reproducible

00:08:53.219 --> 00:08:58.419
results. And then what we do is run the tune race ANOVA function. Its arguments are very,

00:08:58.419 --> 00:09:02.739
very similar to tune grid. The relevant one that's shown here is the grid argument. And

00:09:02.739 --> 00:09:07.539
that could either be an integer that says basically how many tuning parameter combinations

00:09:07.539 --> 00:09:11.500
you want to evaluate and let the function figure out which to do. Or you could pass

00:09:11.500 --> 00:09:15.619
in a data frame there that has the exact combinations that you're interested in.

00:09:15.619 --> 00:09:19.580
There's a control argument that lets you specify a lot of the numerical aspects of things like

00:09:19.580 --> 00:09:23.739
the size of the confidence interval that's used for elimination and so on. There's also

00:09:23.739 --> 00:09:28.219
a verbose elim option that does some logging that shows you the progress as you proceed.

00:09:28.219 --> 00:09:32.619
So you can see there it shows that we eliminated 17 tuning parameter values at the first

00:09:32.619 --> 00:09:38.099
iteration and so on. Now, if you'd like to try the other racing method that's based on

00:09:38.099 --> 00:09:43.580
win-loss statistics, that function is called tune race win-loss. And the syntax is identical

00:09:43.580 --> 00:09:48.659
to what we see here in tune race ANOVA.

00:09:48.659 --> 00:09:53.179
So as I've mentioned, racing is really a grid search method that's done very efficiently.

00:09:53.179 --> 00:09:57.580
And again, in grid search, you predefine all the values you want to look at. So the next

00:09:57.580 --> 00:10:01.500
method we'll talk about is an iterative search method based on simulated annealing where

00:10:01.500 --> 00:10:07.299
new values are determined after each current value. So you don't predefine the tuning parameter

00:10:07.299 --> 00:10:09.179
values.

00:10:09.179 --> 00:10:13.659
So simulated annealing is really a pretty old search routine. And it conducts a bias

00:10:13.659 --> 00:10:18.140
random walk around our tuning parameter space. And the bias comes in because once it creates

00:10:18.140 --> 00:10:25.380
a new tuning parameter candidate and evaluates it, it may discard that from the search and

00:10:25.419 --> 00:10:32.419
pretend like it never existed. Or if the results are not too far from optimal or a new best,

00:10:32.419 --> 00:10:34.820
it would accept that and proceed from there.

00:10:34.820 --> 00:10:40.179
So we'll show that in detail in a little bit as we show the example. One thing we should

00:10:40.179 --> 00:10:45.739
talk about is how simulating comes up with its next value to evaluate. So on the right-hand

00:10:45.739 --> 00:10:49.659
side, we sort of have a plot where the black line shows a search that's gone through six

00:10:49.659 --> 00:10:55.500
iterations and is slowly going down towards the bottom right. And then once we are at

00:10:55.500 --> 00:11:00.260
that last point, we need to generate values that are within a local neighborhood of the

00:11:00.260 --> 00:11:04.140
current best. So what simulated annealing would do would find values that are not too

00:11:04.140 --> 00:11:06.859
different from the one you're currently evaluating.

00:11:06.859 --> 00:11:13.099
So what we've done is we've generated a variety of random combinations that are shown in red

00:11:13.099 --> 00:11:17.340
there that are within some sort of radius around the current best. And then we would

00:11:17.340 --> 00:11:22.099
select one from random as the next point that we should evaluate. Now the bias-random

00:11:22.099 --> 00:11:26.900
walk part comes in because if we select one of those and the performance is not as good

00:11:26.900 --> 00:11:32.099
as the current value, we have two choices. The algorithm can either accept it and proceed

00:11:32.099 --> 00:11:37.780
from it going forward or discard it and again, pretend as if it was never generated.

00:11:37.780 --> 00:11:42.099
And the determining factors for whether we discard or accept a result are based on two

00:11:42.099 --> 00:11:47.419
things. One is how early you are in the search process. So you're much more likely to accept

00:11:47.419 --> 00:11:52.179
suboptimal values at the early parts of the search progress. Um, that's how simulated

00:11:52.179 --> 00:11:57.219
annealing works. And as you get to the later iterations, you're much less likely to accept

00:11:57.219 --> 00:12:03.599
poor values. Now, the second factor in that decision is how bad was the current result.

00:12:03.599 --> 00:12:07.539
So if the current result is just slightly worse than the current best, it's more likely

00:12:07.539 --> 00:12:12.419
that you would accept it. But if it's a really awful point, um, probabilistically it's less

00:12:12.419 --> 00:12:16.340
likely that you would consider that as the current point and base your next point off

00:12:16.340 --> 00:12:22.460
of that one. So we'll show this in some detail with our current example.

00:12:22.460 --> 00:12:26.380
So here's our search space that we looked at earlier. Um, I've generated a grid of four

00:12:26.380 --> 00:12:31.020
different, uh, tuning perimeter values and evaluate them using resampling. Uh, the current

00:12:31.020 --> 00:12:36.700
best from that grid is the green dot. Um, so simulated annealing will start from that

00:12:36.739 --> 00:12:41.179
green dot and proceed from there. So on the first iteration, we're going to define again

00:12:41.179 --> 00:12:46.299
this neighborhood around that green dot and randomly generate a point. And so we did that.

00:12:46.299 --> 00:12:50.580
It actually turns out it's a new best. It's going towards the better results. And so we

00:12:50.580 --> 00:12:57.260
keep that and then base the iteration two results on this value. Now in iteration two,

00:12:57.260 --> 00:13:01.419
we go in kind of a poor direction and get actually fairly bad results. And they're low

00:13:01.419 --> 00:13:05.900
enough to where we would discard this as being suboptimal. And so when we go to iteration

00:13:05.900 --> 00:13:11.179
three, it's based on the results from iteration one, as you'll see in just a second. So discarding

00:13:11.179 --> 00:13:16.460
it means we do not use it to generate the next point in the search.

00:13:16.460 --> 00:13:21.739
So in iteration three, you see we get another new best and then we can keep going around

00:13:21.739 --> 00:13:26.260
the search by finding things that are in a local neighborhood. Now, one of the things

00:13:26.260 --> 00:13:30.179
about simulated annealing is it's a global search method, which means it can go back

00:13:30.179 --> 00:13:36.780
and reevaluate areas that it might have already evaluated. And so in this particular result

00:13:36.780 --> 00:13:42.179
on iteration eight, it goes back in a different direction and we accepted a suboptimal. And

00:13:42.179 --> 00:13:46.099
as you can see, we're going to go into an area that's not very good and we're getting

00:13:46.099 --> 00:13:50.659
a series of just poor results. Now, simulated annealing also has this feature

00:13:50.659 --> 00:13:54.419
where you can do a restart. So if you don't have good results within a certain number

00:13:54.419 --> 00:13:59.340
of iterations, you can trigger the search to start from its last known best point and

00:13:59.340 --> 00:14:03.900
proceed from there. And that is actually what happens here, that we still have another

00:14:03.900 --> 00:14:09.099
suboptimal result. And then we start the search again from the current best.

00:14:09.099 --> 00:14:17.059
And so we proceed along here. It happens again. We go off in a bad direction and then we start.

00:14:17.059 --> 00:14:21.340
And so you can see we're close to the number of iterations. So I did 30 iterations here

00:14:21.340 --> 00:14:27.500
and it would just continue to look until it finds better and better values.

00:14:27.500 --> 00:14:31.299
So that's a little graphical representation of how simulated annealing works. If you want

00:14:31.299 --> 00:14:36.419
to use this in code, the code is very similar to the tune base function in the tune package.

00:14:36.419 --> 00:14:40.580
The arguments are almost all the same. You could tell a number of iterations to proceed

00:14:40.580 --> 00:14:46.140
from. Again, there's another control parameter that determines things like the size of local

00:14:46.140 --> 00:14:50.940
neighborhood and so on. So it has some of the numerical properties that you can tweak

00:14:50.940 --> 00:14:55.340
for simulated annealing. It also has a verbose method. So if you set that to true, you get

00:14:55.340 --> 00:15:00.859
some nice logging as the search continues. What's nice about this is if you're running

00:15:00.859 --> 00:15:04.739
interactively and it's been running for a while and you feel like maybe it's done as

00:15:04.739 --> 00:15:10.380
best as it could do, you can manually interrupt the execution of the tune semineal function

00:15:10.380 --> 00:15:14.780
and it will return all the results that it's achieved so far. So by manually interrupting

00:15:14.780 --> 00:15:18.059
it, you don't lose all the results that you've generated. It will give you the ones that

00:15:18.059 --> 00:15:23.859
you've completed to date. And so that's the other function that we wanted

00:15:23.859 --> 00:15:28.700
to show for model tuning in the fine tune package. If you wanted to learn more, look

00:15:28.700 --> 00:15:33.539
at tidymodels.org. Especially if you're new to Tidy Models, it has a lot of articles on

00:15:33.539 --> 00:15:39.539
getting started, a nice sequence of examples of how to use recipes and parsnip and variety

00:15:39.539 --> 00:15:45.020
of different things. There's other articles there for people who have used it, more advanced

00:15:45.020 --> 00:15:49.340
articles that show different aspects of Tidy Models. Julia Silgi and I are also writing

00:15:49.340 --> 00:15:55.739
a book on Tidy Models. It's about halfway done at the end of 2020. Chapter 13 is about

00:15:55.739 --> 00:15:59.979
grid search and it has more details about racing and chapter 14 is about iterative search

00:15:59.979 --> 00:16:04.099
and one of the things it describes there is seminealing. You can also look at the fine

00:16:04.099 --> 00:16:08.979
tune webpage, which has a nice formatted reference section as well as the blog posts that we

00:16:08.979 --> 00:16:13.179
use to launch the package. Thanks for watching and I hope you enjoy it.

00:16:19.340 --> 00:16:21.340
